---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const b = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, "");
---

<BaseLayout
  title="The Science — TriCel CxnA | iDEC 2025"
  description="Background science: cellulose structure, the three enzyme classes, CxnA's origin, directed evolution, and key literature for the CxnA directed evolution project."
>

  <!-- ═══ PAGE HERO ═══ -->
  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Background Science</p>
      <h1>Cellulose, enzymes, and directed evolution</h1>
      <p>
        The biology behind this project — from cellulose's molecular structure to how we use
        laboratory evolution to engineer new protein functions.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══ CELLULOSE ═══ -->
  <section class="section section--alt" aria-labelledby="cellulose-heading">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <p class="eyebrow">The substrate</p>
        <h2 id="cellulose-heading">What is cellulose, and why is it hard to break down?</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="two-col">
        <div class="prose">
          <p>
            Cellulose is the structural polymer that makes up plant cell walls. Chemically, it
            is a linear chain of glucose molecules linked by <strong>β-1,4 glycosidic bonds</strong>
            — the same building blocks as starch, but connected at a different angle. That
            seemingly small chemical difference is what makes cellulose so recalcitrant.
          </p>
          <p>
            Where starch forms loose, helical coils that are easily digested, cellulose chains
            pack tightly into hydrogen-bonded, crystalline microfibrils. This crystalline
            structure is extraordinarily stable — it resists most chemical and enzymatic
            attack, which is why wood is strong and cotton doesn't dissolve in water.
          </p>
          <p>
            To fully convert cellulose to glucose requires breaking through multiple levels of
            structural complexity: first loosening the crystalline packing, then fragmenting
            the chains, then cleaving the resulting disaccharide cellobiose into free glucose.
            Each step requires a different enzyme class, acting synergistically.
          </p>

          <details class="expand mt-6">
            <summary>Why does the β-1,4 linkage matter so much?</summary>
            <div class="expand-body">
              <p>
                The β configuration at the glycosidic bond causes each glucose unit to rotate
                180° relative to its neighbour, producing an extended, flat ribbon rather
                than a helix. These flat ribbons can stack and hydrogen-bond to each other
                very efficiently, forming the tight crystalline bundles that give cellulose
                its mechanical strength.
              </p>
              <p>
                Animals lack the enzymes (cellulases) to break β-1,4 bonds — which is why
                cows, termites, and other cellulose-eating animals rely on gut microbes that
                do produce cellulases. Fungi and bacteria such as <em>Cellulomonas fimi</em>
                (the source organism of CxnA) are among the most efficient natural cellulose
                degraders known.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
        </div>

        <!-- Cellulose structure diagram -->
        <div>
          <figure class="diagram-figure">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 380 260" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="sci-svg" aria-labelledby="cellulose-svg-title">
              <title id="cellulose-svg-title">Cellulose polymer structure: glucose units linked by β-1,4 glycosidic bonds packing into crystalline microfibrils</title>
              <!-- Chain 1 -->
              <g transform="translate(0,20)">
                <rect x="20" y="60" width="52" height="36" rx="8" fill="#1a6648" opacity="0.9"/>
                <text x="46" y="82" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="white" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif" font-weight="600">Glc</text>
                <!-- bond -->
                <line x1="72" y1="78" x2="95" y2="78" stroke="#7ec9a6" stroke-width="2"/>
                <text x="83" y="72" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#7ec9a6" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">β-1,4</text>
                <rect x="95" y="60" width="52" height="36" rx="8" fill="#1a6648" opacity="0.9"/>
                <text x="121" y="82" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="white" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif" font-weight="600">Glc</text>
                <line x1="147" y1="78" x2="170" y2="78" stroke="#7ec9a6" stroke-width="2"/>
                <text x="158" y="72" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#7ec9a6" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">β-1,4</text>
                <rect x="170" y="60" width="52" height="36" rx="8" fill="#1a6648" opacity="0.9"/>
                <text x="196" y="82" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="white" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif" font-weight="600">Glc</text>
                <line x1="222" y1="78" x2="245" y2="78" stroke="#7ec9a6" stroke-width="2"/>
                <rect x="245" y="60" width="52" height="36" rx="8" fill="#1a6648" opacity="0.7"/>
                <text x="271" y="82" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="white" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif" font-weight="600">Glc</text>
                <text x="308" y="82" text-anchor="start" font-size="14" fill="#4aa87a" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">···</text>
                <!-- Chain label -->
                <text x="10" y="52" font-size="9.5" fill="#5aaa85" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif" font-weight="600">Chain 1</text>
              </g>

              <!-- Chain 2 (offset) -->
              <g transform="translate(18,80)">
                <rect x="20" y="60" width="52" height="36" rx="8" fill="#2b5a40" opacity="0.75"/>
                <text x="46" y="82" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="white" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif" font-weight="600">Glc</text>
                <line x1="72" y1="78" x2="95" y2="78" stroke="#7ec9a6" stroke-width="2" opacity="0.6"/>
                <rect x="95" y="60" width="52" height="36" rx="8" fill="#2b5a40" opacity="0.75"/>
                <text x="121" y="82" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="white" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif" font-weight="600">Glc</text>
                <line x1="147" y1="78" x2="170" y2="78" stroke="#7ec9a6" stroke-width="2" opacity="0.6"/>
                <rect x="170" y="60" width="52" height="36" rx="8" fill="#2b5a40" opacity="0.75"/>
                <text x="196" y="82" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="white" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif" font-weight="600">Glc</text>
                <line x1="222" y1="78" x2="245" y2="78" stroke="#7ec9a6" stroke-width="2" opacity="0.6"/>
                <rect x="245" y="60" width="52" height="36" rx="8" fill="#2b5a40" opacity="0.6"/>
                <text x="271" y="82" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="white" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif" font-weight="600">Glc</text>
                <text x="10" y="52" font-size="9.5" fill="#5aaa85" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif" font-weight="600">Chain 2</text>
              </g>

              <!-- H-bond indicators between chains -->
              <line x1="64" y1="115" x2="56" y2="140" stroke="#a8d5bc" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="3,2"/>
              <line x1="139" y1="115" x2="131" y2="140" stroke="#a8d5bc" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="3,2"/>
              <line x1="214" y1="115" x2="206" y2="140" stroke="#a8d5bc" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="3,2"/>
              <text x="25" y="132" font-size="8" fill="#a8d5bc" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif" font-style="italic">H-bonds</text>

              <!-- Labels -->
              <text x="20" y="235" font-size="9.5" fill="#7ec9a6" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">
                ↕ Hydrogen bonds between chains → crystalline packing
              </text>
              <text x="20" y="252" font-size="9.5" fill="#5aaa85" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">
                Each unit = glucose (C₆H₁₂O₆); β-1,4 linkage flips alternate units 180°
              </text>
            </svg>
            <figcaption>Cellulose polymer: alternating glucose units linked by β-1,4 glycosidic bonds. Hydrogen bonds between parallel chains create the crystalline structure that resists degradation.</figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══ THREE ENZYME TYPES ═══ -->
  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="enzymes-heading">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <p class="eyebrow">The enzyme system</p>
        <h2 id="enzymes-heading">Three enzyme classes — all required, acting in concert</h2>
        <p>
          No single natural enzyme can convert crystalline cellulose to glucose alone.
          A minimum of three activities are required, and they are synergistic — each one
          makes the others more effective.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Three-enzyme pathway diagram -->
      <figure class="pathway-figure" aria-labelledby="pathway-svg-title">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 800 200" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="pathway-svg" aria-labelledby="pathway-svg-title">
          <title id="pathway-svg-title">Cellulose degradation pathway: exoglucanase attacks crystalline cellulose to release cellobiose, endoglucanase cleaves internal bonds, beta-glucosidase converts cellobiose to glucose</title>

          <!-- Stage 1: Crystalline cellulose -->
          <rect x="10" y="50" width="160" height="100" rx="10" fill="#edf3f0" stroke="#c7dcd0" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <text x="90" y="88" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="#2b4f3d" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif" font-weight="700">Crystalline</text>
          <text x="90" y="103" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="#2b4f3d" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif" font-weight="700">Cellulose</text>
          <text x="90" y="122" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#52706a" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">tightly packed fibrils</text>
          <text x="90" y="137" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#52706a" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">highly resistant</text>

          <!-- Arrow 1 -->
          <path d="M170,100 L218,100" stroke="#1a6648" stroke-width="2.5" marker-end="url(#arr1)" fill="none"/>
          <defs>
            <marker id="arr1" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="6" refY="3" orient="auto">
              <path d="M0,0 L0,6 L8,3 z" fill="#1a6648"/>
            </marker>
            <marker id="arr2" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="6" refY="3" orient="auto">
              <path d="M0,0 L0,6 L8,3 z" fill="#1a6648"/>
            </marker>
            <marker id="arr3" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="6" refY="3" orient="auto">
              <path d="M0,0 L0,6 L8,3 z" fill="#c9862a"/>
            </marker>
          </defs>

          <!-- Enzyme label 1 -->
          <rect x="172" y="64" width="44" height="28" rx="5" fill="#1a6648"/>
          <text x="194" y="80" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="white" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif" font-weight="700">Exo-</text>
          <text x="194" y="91" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#a8d5bc" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">GH10/Cex</text>

          <!-- Stage 2: Amorphous + cellobiose -->
          <rect x="220" y="50" width="180" height="100" rx="10" fill="#e8f4ee" stroke="#b0d8c0" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <text x="310" y="82" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10.5" fill="#1a4a35" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif" font-weight="700">Amorphous cellulose</text>
          <text x="310" y="97" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10.5" fill="#1a4a35" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif" font-weight="700">+ cellobiose</text>
          <text x="310" y="116" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#52706a" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">chain ends exposed</text>
          <text x="310" y="131" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#52706a" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">shorter oligomers</text>

          <!-- Arrow 2 (endoglucanase) -->
          <path d="M400,100 L448,100" stroke="#1a6648" stroke-width="2.5" marker-end="url(#arr2)" fill="none"/>
          <rect x="402" y="64" width="44" height="28" rx="5" fill="#1a6648"/>
          <text x="424" y="80" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="white" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif" font-weight="700">Endo-</text>
          <text x="424" y="91" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#a8d5bc" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">GH10/CenA</text>

          <!-- Stage 3: Cellobiose -->
          <rect x="450" y="50" width="150" height="100" rx="10" fill="#e8f4ee" stroke="#b0d8c0" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <text x="525" y="88" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10.5" fill="#1a4a35" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif" font-weight="700">Cellobiose</text>
          <text x="525" y="103" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9.5" fill="#1a4a35" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">(Glc–Glc dimer)</text>
          <text x="525" y="122" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#52706a" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">one step from glucose</text>

          <!-- Arrow 3 (beta-glucosidase) -->
          <path d="M600,100 L648,100" stroke="#c9862a" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-dasharray="6,3" marker-end="url(#arr3)" fill="none"/>
          <rect x="601" y="64" width="46" height="28" rx="5" fill="#8a5a12" stroke="#c9862a" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="4,2"/>
          <text x="624" y="80" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="white" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif" font-weight="700">β-Glcase</text>
          <text x="624" y="91" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#f0c070" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">GH1 (target)</text>

          <!-- Stage 4: Glucose -->
          <rect x="650" y="50" width="140" height="100" rx="10" fill="#fdf0e0" stroke="#c9862a" stroke-width="2"/>
          <text x="720" y="88" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="#7a3a08" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif" font-weight="700">Glucose</text>
          <text x="720" y="103" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9.5" fill="#a05010" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">fermentable sugar</text>
          <text x="720" y="122" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#b45309" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">usable for biofuel</text>

          <!-- Legend -->
          <rect x="10" y="170" width="12" height="12" rx="2" fill="#1a6648"/>
          <text x="27" y="181" font-size="9" fill="#52706a" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">Existing in CxnA WT</text>
          <rect x="160" y="170" width="12" height="12" rx="2" fill="none" stroke="#c9862a" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="4,2"/>
          <text x="177" y="181" font-size="9" fill="#52706a" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">Project A target — not yet present in CxnA</text>
        </svg>
        <figcaption>
          Complete cellulose degradation pathway. Exo- and endoglucanases (both present in CxnA wild-type) act synergistically
          on crystalline and amorphous cellulose. Beta-glucosidase (Project A target) completes the pathway to free glucose.
        </figcaption>
      </figure>

      <!-- Three enzyme cards -->
      <div class="grid-3 mt-10">
        <div class="enzyme-card">
          <div class="enzyme-badge">GH10 / Cex</div>
          <h3>Exoglucanase</h3>
          <p class="enzyme-status"><span class="badge badge--confirmed">Present in CxnA WT</span></p>
          <p>
            Attacks crystalline cellulose from the non-reducing ends of chains, processively
            releasing the disaccharide cellobiose. Particularly important for initiating
            degradation of the crystalline fraction.
          </p>
          <details class="expand mt-4">
            <summary>Structural and mechanistic detail</summary>
            <div class="expand-body">
              <p>
                The Cex (exoglucanase) domain of CxnA belongs to glycoside hydrolase family
                GH10. GH10 enzymes use a retaining double-displacement mechanism, with two
                conserved glutamate residues (GLU127 as nucleophile and GLU233 as acid/base
                in this project's structural model) coordinating catalysis.
                <a class="cite" href="#ref-notenboom" aria-label="Reference 3: Notenboom et al. 1998">[3]</a>
              </p>
              <p>
                The active-site tunnel topology of exoglucanases enables processive movement
                along the cellulose chain, explaining their preference for crystalline
                rather than amorphous substrates.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
        </div>

        <div class="enzyme-card">
          <div class="enzyme-badge">GH10 / CenA</div>
          <h3>Endoglucanase</h3>
          <p class="enzyme-status"><span class="badge badge--confirmed">Present in CxnA WT</span></p>
          <p>
            Cleaves β-1,4 bonds at internal positions within the cellulose chain — not at the
            ends. This creates new chain ends that the exoglucanase can then attack, making
            the two activities strongly synergistic.
          </p>
          <details class="expand mt-4">
            <summary>Structural and mechanistic detail</summary>
            <div class="expand-body">
              <p>
                CenA-type endoglucanases have an open active-site cleft (rather than a tunnel),
                which enables them to bind and cleave internal bonds. CxnA uniquely combines
                Cex and CenA activities in a single polypeptide, which is the starting point
                for this project.
                <a class="cite" href="#ref-duedu" aria-label="Reference 1: Duedu &amp; French 2016">[1]</a>
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
        </div>

        <div class="enzyme-card enzyme-card--target">
          <div class="enzyme-badge enzyme-badge--target">GH1 / BGL</div>
          <h3>Beta-glucosidase</h3>
          <p class="enzyme-status"><span class="badge badge--progress">Project A target</span></p>
          <p>
            Converts the disaccharide cellobiose into two glucose molecules. This is the final
            step in converting cellulose to fermentable sugar, and the activity this project
            is attempting to evolve into CxnA.
          </p>
          <details class="expand mt-4">
            <summary>Structural and mechanistic detail</summary>
            <div class="expand-body">
              <p>
                GH1 family beta-glucosidases also use a retaining mechanism, with two
                glutamate residues (catalytic nucleophile and acid/base). In this project's
                structural model, GLU350 and GLU404 are identified as candidate positions.
                <a class="cite" href="#ref-liu" aria-label="Reference 4: Liu et al. 2018">[4]</a>
              </p>
              <p>
                A key finding from the docking analysis is the steric barrier formed by GLN87
                and TRP281, which may limit cellobiose access to the active site. Understanding
                and potentially overcoming this barrier is central to Project A's strategy.
                See the <a href={`${b}/results#drylab-gh1`}>Results page</a> for full discussion.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══ CxnA ORIGIN ═══ -->
  <section class="section section--alt" aria-labelledby="cxna-heading">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <p class="eyebrow">Our starting enzyme</p>
        <h2 id="cxna-heading">CxnA: a naturally bifunctional cellulase</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="two-col">
        <div class="prose">
          <p>
            CxnA was originally described by Duedu &amp; French at the University of Edinburgh
            in 2016.
            <a class="cite" href="#ref-duedu" aria-label="Reference 1: Duedu &amp; French 2016">[1]</a>
            It was isolated from <em>Cellulomonas fimi</em>, a Gram-positive soil bacterium
            that is one of the most efficient natural cellulose degraders known, and notable
            for producing a sophisticated multi-enzyme cellulose-degrading system.
          </p>
          <p>
            What makes CxnA unusual is that it naturally combines two distinct catalytic
            activities — exoglucanase and endoglucanase — in a single polypeptide chain.
            Most organisms deploy these as separate enzymes. CxnA demonstrates that the
            architecture is achievable, and raises the question of whether the same protein
            could be evolved to accommodate a third.
          </p>
          <p>
            The domain architecture of CxnA, as established by Duedu &amp; French and refined
            in this project using AlphaFold3, comprises a GH10 catalytic domain (bearing both
            Cex-type and CenA-type activities) and a GH1-fold domain that is the target for
            directed evolution in Project A.
          </p>

          <div class="callout mt-6">
            <p class="callout-title">Key datum: Structural validation</p>
            <p>
              The AlphaFold3 model of the GH10/Cex domain was validated against the
              published crystal structure 1FHD (Notenboom et al., 1998
              <a class="cite" href="#ref-notenboom" aria-label="Reference 3: Notenboom 1998">[3]</a>).
              RMSD = <strong>0.293 Å</strong> over aligned Cα atoms — indicating
              high structural accuracy and supporting the reliability of downstream
              docking predictions. See <a href={`${b}/results#drylab-structure`}>Results</a>
              for full validation analysis.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="cxna-card card">
          <h4 class="card-label">CxnA at a glance</h4>
          <table class="info-table">
            <tbody>
              <tr><th>Source organism</th><td><em>Cellulomonas fimi</em></td></tr>
              <tr><th>Original reference</th><td>Duedu &amp; French, 2016 <a class="cite" href="#ref-duedu">[1]</a></td></tr>
              <tr><th>Institution</th><td>University of Edinburgh</td></tr>
              <tr><th>Domain 1</th><td>GH10 (exo- and endoglucanase)</td></tr>
              <tr><th>Domain 2</th><td>GH1-fold (catalytically inactive in WT for GH1-type activity)</td></tr>
              <tr><th>Natural function</th><td>Bifunctional cellulose degradation</td></tr>
              <tr><th>Crystal structure ref</th><td>1FHD (GH10/Cex, Notenboom 1998 <a class="cite" href="#ref-notenboom">[3]</a>)</td></tr>
              <tr><th>AlphaFold3 RMSD vs 1FHD</th><td class="mono"><strong>0.293 Å</strong> (validated)</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══ DIRECTED EVOLUTION ═══ -->
  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="devc-heading">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <p class="eyebrow">The method</p>
        <h2 id="devc-heading">What is directed evolution?</h2>
        <p>
          A laboratory technique that mimics natural selection — but compressed into weeks,
          and directed toward a specific functional goal.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="two-col">
        <div>
          <div class="de-steps">
            <div class="de-step">
              <div class="de-step-num" aria-hidden="true">1</div>
              <div>
                <h3>Introduce random mutations</h3>
                <p>
                  Error-prone PCR (epPCR) amplifies the target gene with a deliberately elevated
                  error rate, creating a library of thousands of sequence variants — each a slightly
                  different version of the protein. This is analogous to natural mutation, but we
                  control the rate.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="de-step">
              <div class="de-step-num" aria-hidden="true">2</div>
              <div>
                <h3>Apply selection pressure</h3>
                <p>
                  The mutant library is expressed in bacteria, which are then challenged with a
                  condition that only cells expressing the desired activity can survive or grow
                  well under. For Project A: growth on cellobiose as sole carbon source. For
                  Project B: enhanced zone-clearing on CMC plates.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="de-step">
              <div class="de-step-num" aria-hidden="true">3</div>
              <div>
                <h3>Screen survivors</h3>
                <p>
                  Colonies that grow are screened with fluorogenic substrates (MUG for
                  beta-glucosidase, MUC for exoglucanase) to quantify activity. False
                  positives — cells that grew for reasons unrelated to the target activity —
                  are identified and eliminated.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="de-step">
              <div class="de-step-num" aria-hidden="true">4</div>
              <div>
                <h3>Characterise and iterate</h3>
                <p>
                  Hits are sequenced to identify which mutations confer the activity, then
                  validated in purified enzyme assays. The best variants can then be subjected
                  to another round of mutagenesis — iterating toward the desired function.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="prose">
          <h3>Why directed evolution works</h3>
          <p>
            Natural evolution explores protein sequence space over millions of generations
            and years. Directed evolution recapitulates this process in the lab by:
            deliberately narrowing the sequence space explored (we start from a protein that
            already has related structure), applying strong artificial selection pressure
            (survival on a specific substrate), and iterating rapidly (weeks, not millennia).
          </p>
          <p>
            The key insight is that <strong>you don't need to rationally design every
            mutation</strong>. The selection/screening step acts as the filter — you just
            need to generate enough sequence diversity that beneficial mutations exist
            somewhere in the library, and then find them.
          </p>
          <p>
            This project also uses computational structural analysis (AlphaFold3 + docking)
            to <em>guide</em> the mutagenesis — targeting epPCR to the regions most likely
            to be functionally important, reducing the haystack that selection must search.
          </p>
          <div class="callout callout--warn mt-6">
            <p class="callout-title">Important limitation</p>
            <p>
              Computational predictions guide but cannot replace experimental selection.
              Docking scores predict approximate binding geometry; they do not predict whether
              a mutation will actually confer catalytic activity in a living cell. All
              computational findings in this project are treated as hypotheses to be tested
              in the wet lab, not as conclusions.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══ KEY LITERATURE ═══ -->
